The probability of side $i$ appearing on the $i$th trial in any single roll of an $n$-sided die is $P(M_i) = 1/n$. Since the $n$ rolls are independent, the probability that side $i$ does not appear on the $i$th trial for all $i=1, 2, \ldots, n$ is:
$$P(\text{no match}) = \prod_{i=1}^n P(M_i^c) = \prod_{i=1}^n \left(1 - \frac{1}{n}\right) = \left(1 - \frac{1}{n}\right)^n$$
A match occurs if at least one side $i$ is observed on the $i$th trial. The probability of at least one match is:
$$P(\text{at least one match}) = 1 - P(\text{no match}) = 1 - \left(1 - \frac{1}{n}\right)^n$$
To find the limit as $n$ increases without bound:
$$\lim_{n \to \infty} \left[1 - \left(1 - \frac{1}{n}\right)^n\right] = 1 - \lim_{n \to \infty} \left(1 - \frac{1}{n}\right)^n$$
Using the standard limit $\lim_{n \to \infty} (1 + x/n)^n = e^x$, we have:
$$\lim_{n \to \infty} \left(1 - \frac{1}{n}\right)^n = e^{-1} = \frac{1}{e}$$
Thus, the limit of the probability is:
$$1 - \frac{1}{e} \approx 1 - 0.36787944117 = 0.63212055882 \dots$$
Based on the solution provided, the final answer is $0.6321205588$.

